==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*gans'', from Indo-European ''*g̑ʰans-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[gos#Old Frisian|gōs]], Middle Dutch [[gans]] (Dutch [[gans]]), Old High German [[gans]] (German [[Gans]]), Old Norse [[gás]] (Swedish [[gås]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Avestan ''zā'', Greek [[χήν]], Latin [[anser|ānser]], Russian [[гусь]], Latvian [[zuoss|zùoss]], Old Irish [[géiss]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /go:s/

===Noun===
'''gōs''' ''f''
# a [[goose]]
#:''Hwilum ic græde swa gos'': sometimes I cry as a goose.  (''Exeter Book'')

